[[File:Japanese Union Church, Los Angeles.jpg|thumb|The Union Center for the Arts (former Japanese Union Church) on [[John F. Aiso|Judge John Aiso Street]]]] '''San Pedro Street''' is a major north-south thoroughfare in [[Los Angeles, California]], running from [[Little Tokyo, Los Angeles|Little Tokyo]] in [[Downtown Los Angeles]] to [[West Rancho Dominguez, California|West Rancho Dominguez]]. San Pedro Street was one of the earliest roadways, along with [[Alameda Street]], between central Los Angeles and the [[Port of Los Angeles]]; much of the road's original alignment south of [[Jefferson Boulevard]] has been renamed [[Avalon Boulevard]].
The portion of San Pedro Street north of 1st Street was renamed [[John F. Aiso|Judge John Aiso]] Street in 1999.
==Landmarks==
* [[Edward R. Roybal Federal Building and United States Courthouse]] * [[List of Los Angeles Historic-Cultural Monuments in Downtown Los Angeles#Japanese Union Church of Los Angeles|Union Center for the Arts]] (former Japanese Union Church of Los Angeles) * [[List of Los Angeles Historic-Cultural Monuments in Downtown Los Angeles#San Pedro Firm Building|San Pedro Firm Building]] * [[Little Tokyo, Los Angeles|Little Tokyo]] * Japanese American Cultural & Community Center * The Japanese American Veterans Memorial Court * [[James Irvine (landowner)|James Irvine]] Japanese Garden * [[Toy District, Los Angeles|Toy District]] * [[Skid Row, Los Angeles|Skid Row]] * [[Fashion District, Los Angeles|Fashion District]]
==Public transportation== [[Metro Local]] lines 48, 51, 52 and 351 serve San Pedro Street; Line 48 runs in South LA and lines 51, 52 and 351 in Downtown LA.
The [[Blue Line (Los Angeles Metro)|Metro Blue Line]] serves a light rail [[San Pedro (LACMTA station) |station]] in the center median of Washington Boulevard about half a block east of that street.
